# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fabrik-inc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] The consortium's bid was centered around the Class 800 and 801 high speed trains, which provided more seats, reduced journey times, and superior environmental performance than the Intercity 125 sets.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] The bid submitted by the consortium was successful, leading to the finalising of a £4.5bn contract in mid 2012 to produce and sustain trains for both the Great Western Main Line (GWML) and East Coast Main Line (ECML).
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] Infrastructure built to fulfil the contract included a new manufacturing site at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe and multiple new depots to maintain the fleet.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] In October 2017, the first train went into service on the GWML.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] Agility Trains was formed in response to the Intercity Express Programme (IEP), launched by the Department for Transport (DfT) in 2005 with the initial goal of procuring a replacement for the aging Intercity 125 fleet on both the Great Western Main Line and East Coast Main Line.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] On 16 November 2007, the DfT issued an Invitation to Tender for the IEP to three shortlisted entities: Alstom-Barclays Rail Group; Express Rail Alliance (Bombardier, Siemens, Angel Trains and Babcock & Brown); and Agility Trains.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] Shortly after Alstom's decision to withdraw from the bidding in February 2008, British investment firm Barclays Private Equity opted to re-enter the IEP on 26 June 2008, four days before the end of the bidding process, as a partner of Hitachi and John Laing, in Agility Trains.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] The finalised £4.5bn contract for trains for the GWML and ECML was announced in July 2012.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] Assembly of most of the trains took place in the UK, using Japanese-built bodyshells, with a new factory being established at Hitachi Newton Aycliffe.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] Additionally, new depots to maintain the new train fleet were also developed.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] The first IEP train left the Kasado factory on 7 January 2015 for shipping via Kobe, In October 2017, the first train went into service on the Great Western Main Line.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] In May 2019, the first train entered service on the East Coast Main Line between London King's Cross and Leeds.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] Several ownership changes took place during the late 2010s and early 2020s. in March 2018, Axa announced that it would purchase half of John Laing Group's shareholding in the consortium.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] In September 2020, John Laing Group announced that it was selling its remaining stake in Agility Trains to AIP Management in exchange for £421 million in cash.
[src:fabrik-inc/agility-trains] In November 2021, GLIL Infrastructure purchased a 30% stake in Agility Trains from Hitachi; as a result, Hitachi's stake dropped to 40 percent while GLIL and AIP owning a 30% stake each.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] In 2004, Alaxala Networks Corp. was originally established, as the merger between Hitachi and NEC networking hardware divisions.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] The name of **Alaxala** was derived from "ALL Access for eXpert and Latent Association", and more that "Ala" in Latin means "Wing", and "X" means "networking eXchange", so the company intended the two "Ala" (Hitachi and NEC) connected and collaborated by "X" tightly.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] The company is basically fabless company, designing the products, mostly ordering to manufacture them to Hitachi enterprise servers division factory in Hadano, Kanagawa, Japan.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] The company offers networking hardware products, network router and network switch etc.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] Alaxala products are sold and installed mostly in Japanese domestic market and for enterprises, but we can find several products at some online shopping, Amazon.com etc..
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] The business type and scope is same as Allied Telesis, that is also the company in Japan.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] And they are collaborated for producing networking hardware sold in both brands.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] Alaxala official agencies are Hitachi, NEC, Itochu Techno-Solutions, Net One Systems, and Alaxala has contributed to offer the various networking hardware products to major communication companies in Japan, such as NTT, KDDI, Softbank, and others.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] On August 24, 2012, Alaxala was known that Tokyo Stock Exchange (TSE) announced that TSE core system outage happened due to the software bugs on Alaxala networking hardware.
[src:fabrik-inc/alaxala-networks] Alaxala also sponsors IT professional certifications for Alaxala products, like Cisco, Oracle, and others.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] The company name was changed from **Hitachi Astemo, Ltd.** to Astemo, Ltd. on April 1, 2025.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo was established in January 2021 as a global automotive components manufacturer through the business merger of Hitachi Automotive Systems, Keihin Corporation, Showa Corporation, and Nissin Kogyo.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] The name "Astemo" stands for "Advanced Sustainable Technologies for Mobility", reflecting the company's focus on technologies related to connected, autonomous, shared and electric mobility.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo develops automotive technologies aligned with the industry trends of connectivity, autonomous systems and electrification, with a focus on both passenger and motorcycle applications.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo's ownership structure includes major stakes from both Hitachi, Ltd. and Honda Motor Co., Ltd., each holding 40%, with JIC Capital holding the remaining 20%.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] While Astemo includes former Honda-affiliated parts manufacturers, it also maintains business relationships with Nissan Motor Co., reflecting Hitachi's historical ties to the Nissan Group.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] In December 2025, Honda announced it would acquire an additional 21% of Astemo shares from Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] As a result, the shareholding structure of Astemo will change to 61% for Honda, 20% for JIC, and 19% for Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo has expanded its research and development activities in electric powertrains, advanced driver-assistance systems, and in-vehicle software.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] These efforts support its strategic focus on electrification and autonomous mobility.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] The company has also pursued partnerships and vertical integration to address industry competition and supply chain challenges.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] In December 2024, the Government of Cantabria awarded the Hitachi Astemo Buelna plant a €1 million grant through SODERCAN’s competitive programme for major industrial competitiveness projects.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] The funding supports a €5 million experimental development project focused on advanced braking systems, to be completed over 18 months.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] This initiative underlines the region’s strategic support for automotive innovation and sustainability efforts.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo develops components for electric and autonomous vehicles, with a focus on integration of key systems such as power control units, motors, inverters, and software-defined vehicle platforms.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] The company also emphasizes model-based systems engineering and virtual validation to shorten development timelines and reduce prototyping costs.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] In 2023, Astemo announced a ¥15.3 billion (~US $100 million) expansion of its Berea, Kentucky plant to support its electrification business.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] In July 2025, Astemo announced a £100 million investment in its Horwich manufacturing facility in Bolton, Greater Manchester.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] The project will establish a new production line dedicated to electric vehicle (EV) inverters, making the site the only facility in the United Kingdom with this production capability.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] As of 2025, Astemo operates over 100 business sites globally, including manufacturing plants, R&D centers and regional offices across Asia, Europe and the Americas.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo's facilities span over 25 countries, including sites in Mexico, France, Brazil, Thailand and Vietnam.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] A complete list is available on the Astemo Global Network.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] In September 2025, *CBS News* and *The Detroit News* reported that Astemo planned to establish a regional headquarters in Wixom, Michigan, as part of a $95 million investment expected to create about 200 jobs.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Hitachi Astemo sponsors Team Penske in NTT IndyCar Series in the U.S.A.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo also sponsors Real Racing in the Super GT GT500 class and S.I.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] RACING in the MFJ All Japan Road Race Championship Series.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Astemo owns the Japanese women's volleyball team "Hitachi Astemo Rivale" and sponsors Mie Honda Heat, a Japanese rugby union team based in Suzuka City.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] On December 21, 2021, Hitachi Astemo admitted to falsifying inspection data on brake and suspension components.
[src:fabrik-inc/astemo] Over 50,000 instances of improper testing were identified, dating back to 2003.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] In information technology, a **backup**, or **data backup** is a copy of computer data taken and stored elsewhere so that it may be used to **restore** the original after a data loss event.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The verb form, referring to the process of doing so, is "back up", whereas the noun and adjective form is "backup".
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Backups can be used to recover data after its loss from data deletion or corruption, or to recover data from an earlier time.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Backups provide a simple form of IT disaster recovery; however not all backup systems are able to reconstitute a computer system or other complex configuration such as a computer cluster, active directory server, or database server.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A backup system contains at least one copy of all data considered worth saving.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The data storage requirements can be large.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] An information repository model may be used to provide structure to this storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] There are different types of data storage devices used for copying backups of data that is already in secondary storage onto archive files.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] There are also different ways these devices can be arranged to provide geographic dispersion, data security, and portability.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Data is selected, extracted, and manipulated for storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The process can include methods for dealing with live data, including open files, as well as compression, encryption, and de-duplication.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Additional techniques apply to enterprise client-server backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Backup schemes may include dry runs that validate the reliability of the data being backed up.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] There are limitations and human factors involved in any backup scheme.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A backup strategy requires an information repository, "a secondary storage space for data" that aggregates backups of data "sources".
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The repository could be as simple as a list of all backup media (DVDs, etc.) and the dates produced, or could include a computerized index, catalog, or relational database.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The backup data needs to be stored, requiring a backup rotation scheme, which is a system of backing up data to computer media that limits the number of backups of different dates retained separately, by appropriate re-use of the data storage media by overwriting of backups no longer needed.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The scheme determines how and when each piece of removable storage is used for a backup operation and how long it is retained once it has backup data stored on it.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The 3-2-1 rule can aid in the backup process.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] It states that there should be at least 3 copies of the data, stored on 2 different types of storage media, and one copy should be kept offsite, in a remote location (this can include cloud storage).
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] 2 or more different media should be used to eliminate data loss due to similar reasons (for example, optical discs may tolerate being underwater while LTO tapes may not, and SSDs cannot fail due to head crashes or damaged spindle motors since they do not have any moving parts, unlike hard drives).
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] An offsite copy protects against fire, theft of physical media (such as tapes or discs) and natural disasters like floods and earthquakes.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Physically protected hard drives are an alternative to an offsite copy, but they have limitations like only being able to resist fire for a limited period of time, so an offsite copy still remains as the ideal choice.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Because there is no perfect storage, many backup experts recommend maintaining a second copy on a local physical device, even if the data is also backed up offsite.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] An unstructured repository may simply be a stack of tapes, DVD-Rs or external HDDs with minimal information about what was backed up and when.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This method is the easiest to implement, but unlikely to achieve a high level of recoverability as it lacks automation.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A repository using this backup method contains complete source data copies taken at one or more specific points in time.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Copying system images, this method is frequently used by computer technicians to record known good configurations.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] However, imaging is generally more useful as a way of deploying a standard configuration to many systems rather than as a tool for making ongoing backups of diverse systems.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] An incremental backup stores data changed since a reference point in time.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Duplicate copies of unchanged data are not copied.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Typically a full backup of all files is made once or at infrequent intervals, serving as the reference point for an incremental repository.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Subsequently, a number of incremental backups are made after successive time periods.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Restores begin with the last full backup and then apply the incrementals.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Some backup systems can create a synthetic full backup from a series of incrementals, thus providing the equivalent of frequently doing a full backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] When done to modify a single archive file, this speeds restores of recent versions of files.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Continuous Data Protection (CDP) refers to a backup that instantly saves a copy of every change made to the data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This allows restoration of data to any point in time and is the most comprehensive and advanced data protection.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Near-CDP backup applications—often marketed as "CDP"—automatically take incremental backups at a specific interval, for example every 15 minutes, one hour, or 24 hours.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] They can therefore only allow restores to an interval boundary.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Near-CDP backup applications use journaling and are typically based on periodic "snapshots", read-only copies of the data frozen at a particular point in time.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Near-CDP (except for Apple Time Machine) intent-logs every change on the host system, often by saving byte or block-level differences rather than file-level differences.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This backup method differs from simple disk mirroring in that it enables a roll-back of the log and thus a restoration of old images of data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Near-CDP is more practicable for ordinary personal backup applications, as opposed to *true* CDP, which must be run in conjunction with a virtual machine or equivalent and is therefore generally used in enterprise client-server backups.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Software may create copies of individual files such as written documents, multimedia projects, or user preferences, to prevent failed write events caused by power outages, operating system crashes, or exhausted disk space, from causing data loss.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A common implementation is an appended ".bak" extension to the file name.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A Reverse incremental backup method stores a recent archive file "mirror" of the source data and a series of differences between the "mirror" in its current state and its previous states.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A reverse incremental backup method starts with a non-image full backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] After the full backup is performed, the system periodically synchronizes the full backup with the live copy, while storing the data necessary to reconstruct older versions.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This can either be done using hard links—as Apple Time Machine does, or using binary diffs.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A differential backup saves only the data that has changed since the last full backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This means a maximum of two backups from the repository are used to restore the data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] However, as time from the last full backup (and thus the accumulated changes in data) increases, so does the time to perform the differential backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Restoring an entire system requires starting from the most recent full backup and then applying just the last differential backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Changes in files may be detected through a more recent date/time of last modification file attribute, and/or changes in file size.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Other variations of incremental backup include multi-level incrementals and block-level incrementals that compare parts of files instead of just entire files.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Regardless of the repository model that is used, the data has to be copied onto an archive file data storage medium.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The medium used is also referred to as the type of backup destination.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Magnetic tape was for a long time the most commonly used medium for bulk data storage, backup, archiving, and interchange.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] It was previously a less expensive option, but this is no longer the case for smaller amounts of data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Tape is a sequential access medium, so the rate of continuously writing or reading data can be very fast.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] While tape media itself has a low cost per space, tape drives are typically dozens of times as expensive as hard disk drives and optical drives.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Tape media are generally rotated on a schedule so at least one set is off-site in case something should happen to the building where the primary copy of the data lives.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Many tape formats have been proprietary or specific to certain markets like mainframes or a particular brand of personal computer.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] By 2014 LTO had become the primary tape technology.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The other remaining viable "super" format is the IBM 3592 (also referred to as the TS11xx series).
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The Oracle StorageTek T10000 was discontinued in 2016.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The use of hard disk storage has increased over time as it has become progressively cheaper.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Hard disks are usually easy to use, widely available, and can be accessed quickly.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] However, hard disk backups are close-tolerance mechanical devices and may be more easily damaged than tapes, especially while being transported.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Some manufacturers also offer 'ruggedized' portable hard drives, which include a shock-absorbing case around the hard disk, and claim a range of higher drop specifications.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Over a period of years the stability of hard disk backups is shorter than that of tape backups.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] External hard disks can be connected via local interfaces like SCSI, USB, FireWire, or eSATA, or via longer-distance technologies like Ethernet, iSCSI, or Fibre Channel.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Some disk-based backup systems, via Virtual Tape Libraries or otherwise, support data deduplication, which can reduce the amount of disk storage capacity consumed by daily and weekly backup data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Optical storage uses lasers to store and retrieve data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Recordable CDs, DVDs, and Blu-ray Discs are commonly used with personal computers and are generally cheap.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The capacities and speeds of these discs have typically been lower than hard disks or tapes.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Advances in optical media may shrink that gap in the future.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Potential future data losses caused by gradual media degradation can be predicted by measuring the rate of correctable minor data errors, of which consecutively too many increase the risk of uncorrectable sectors.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Support for error scanning varies among optical drive vendors.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Many optical disc formats are WORM type, which makes them useful for archival purposes since the data cannot be changed in any way, including by user error and by malware such as ransomware.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Moreover, optical discs are not vulnerable to head crashes, magnetism, imminent water ingress or power surges; and, a fault of the drive typically just halts the spinning.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Optical media is modular; the storage controller is not tied to media itself like with hard drives or flash storage (→flash memory controller), allowing it to be removed and accessed through a different drive.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] However, recordable media may degrade earlier under long-term exposure to light.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Some optical storage systems allow for cataloged data backups without human contact with the discs, allowing for longer data integrity.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A French study in 2008 indicated that the lifespan of typically-sold CD-Rs was 2–10 years, but one manufacturer later estimated the longevity of its CD-Rs with a gold-sputtered layer to be as high as 100 years.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Sony's proprietary Optical Disc Archive can in 2016 reach a read rate of 250 MB/s.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Solid-state drives (SSDs) use integrated circuit assemblies to store data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Flash memory, thumb drives, USB flash drives, CompactFlash, SmartMedia, Memory Sticks, and Secure Digital card devices are relatively expensive for their low capacity, but convenient for backing up relatively low data volumes.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A solid-state drive does not contain any movable parts, making it less susceptible to physical damage, and can have huge throughput of around 500 Mbit/s up to 6 Gbit/s.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Available SSDs have become more capacious and cheaper.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Flash memory backups are stable for fewer years than hard disk backups.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Remote backup services or cloud backups involve service providers storing data offsite.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This has been used to protect against events such as fires, floods, or earthquakes which could destroy locally stored backups.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Cloud-based backup (through services like or similar to Google Drive, and Microsoft OneDrive) provides a layer of data protection.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] However, the users must trust the provider to maintain the privacy and integrity of their data, with confidentiality enhanced by the use of encryption.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Because speed and availability are limited by a user's online connection, users with large amounts of data may need to use seed loading and bulk restore.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Various methods can be used to manage backup media, striking a balance between accessibility, security and cost.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] These media management methods are not mutually exclusive and are frequently combined to meet the user's needs.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Using on-line disks for staging data before it is sent to a near-line tape library is a common example.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Online backup storage is typically the most accessible type of data storage, and can begin a restore in milliseconds.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] An internal hard disk or a disk array (maybe connected to SAN) is an example of an online backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This type of storage is convenient and speedy, but is vulnerable to being deleted or overwritten, either by accident, by malevolent action, or in the wake of a data-deleting virus payload.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Nearline storage is typically less accessible and less expensive than online storage, but still useful for backup data storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A mechanical device is usually used to move media units from storage into a drive where the data can be read or written.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Generally it has safety properties similar to on-line storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] An example is a tape library with restore times ranging from seconds to a few minutes.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Off-line storage requires some direct action to provide access to the storage media: for example, inserting a tape into a tape drive or plugging in a cable.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Because the data is not accessible via any computer except during limited periods in which they are written or read back, they are largely immune to on-line backup failure modes.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Access time varies depending on whether the media are on-site or off-site.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Backup media may be sent to an off-site vault to protect against a disaster or other site-specific problem.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The vault can be as simple as a system administrator's home office or as sophisticated as a disaster-hardened, temperature-controlled, high-security bunker with facilities for backup media storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A data replica can be off-site but also on-line (e.g., an off-site RAID mirror).
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A backup site or disaster recovery center is used to store data that can enable computer systems and networks to be restored and properly configured in the event of a disaster.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Some organisations have their own data recovery centres, while others contract this out to a third-party.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Due to high costs, backing up is rarely considered the preferred method of moving data to a DR site.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A more typical way would be remote disk mirroring, which keeps the DR data as up to date as possible.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A backup operation starts with selecting and extracting coherent units of data.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Most data on modern computer systems is stored in discrete units, known as files.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] These files are organized into filesystems.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Deciding what to back up at any given time involves tradeoffs.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] By backing up too much redundant data, the information repository will fill up too quickly.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Backing up an insufficient amount of data can eventually lead to the loss of critical information.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Files that are actively being updated present a challenge to back up.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] One way to back up live data is to temporarily quiesce them (e.g., close all files), take a "snapshot", and then resume live operations.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] At this point the snapshot can be backed up through normal methods.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] A snapshot is an instantaneous function of some filesystems that presents a copy of the filesystem as if it were frozen at a specific point in time, often by a copy-on-write mechanism.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Snapshotting a file while it is being changed results in a corrupted file that is unusable.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This is also the case across interrelated files, as may be found in a conventional database or in applications such as Microsoft Exchange Server.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The term fuzzy backup can be used to describe a backup of live data that looks like it ran correctly, but does not represent the state of the data at a single point in time.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Not all information stored on the computer is stored in files.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Accurately recovering a complete system from scratch requires keeping track of this non-file data too.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] It is frequently useful or required to manipulate the data being backed up to optimize the backup process.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] These manipulations can improve backup speed, restore speed, data security, media usage and/or reduced bandwidth requirements.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Out-of-date data can be automatically deleted, but for personal backup applications—as opposed to enterprise client-server backup applications where automated data "grooming" can be customized—the deletion can at most be globally delayed or be disabled.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Various schemes can be employed to shrink the size of the source data to be stored so that it uses less storage space.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Compression is frequently a built-in feature of tape drive hardware.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Redundancy due to backing up similarly configured workstations can be reduced, thus storing just one copy.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This technique can be applied at the file or raw block level.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This potentially large reduction is called deduplication.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] It can occur on a server before any data moves to backup media, sometimes referred to as source/client side deduplication.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This approach also reduces bandwidth required to send backup data to its target media.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The process can also occur at the target storage device, sometimes referred to as inline or back-end deduplication.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Sometimes backups are duplicated to a second set of storage media.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This can be done to rearrange the archive files to optimize restore speed, or to have a second copy at a different location or on a different storage medium—as in the disk-to-disk-to-tape capability of Enterprise client-server backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] High-capacity removable storage media such as backup tapes present a data security risk if they are lost or stolen.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Encrypting the data on these media can mitigate this problem, however encryption is a CPU intensive process that can slow down backup speeds, and the security of the encrypted backups is only as effective as the security of the key management policy.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] When there are many more computers to be backed up than there are destination storage devices, the ability to use a single storage device with several simultaneous backups can be useful.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] However cramming the scheduled backup window via "multiplexed backup" is only used for tape destinations.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] The process of rearranging the sets of backups in an archive file is known as refactoring.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] For example, if a backup system uses a single tape each day to store the incremental backups for all the protected computers, restoring one of the computers could require many tapes.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Refactoring could be used to consolidate all the backups for a single computer onto a single tape, creating a "synthetic full backup".
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This is especially useful for backup systems that do incrementals forever style backups.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] Sometimes backups are copied to a staging disk before being copied to tape.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] This process is sometimes referred to as D2D2T, an acronym for Disk-to-disk-to-tape.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] It can be useful if there is a problem matching the speed of the final destination device with the source device, as is frequently faced in network-based backup systems.
[src:fabrik-inc/backup] It can also serve as a centralized location for applying other data manipulation techniques.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish has a 64-bit block size and therefore it could be vulnerable to Sweet32 birthday attacks.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Schneier designed Blowfish as a general-purpose algorithm, intended as an alternative to the aging DES and free of the problems and constraints associated with other algorithms.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] At the time Blowfish was released, many other designs were proprietary, encumbered by patents, or were commercial or government secrets.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Schneier has stated that "Blowfish is unpatented, and will remain so in all countries.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Notable features of the design include key-dependent S-boxes and a highly complex key schedule.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish has a 64-bit block size and a variable key length from 32 bits up to 448 bits.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] It is a 16-round Feistel cipher and uses large key-dependent S-boxes.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] In structure it resembles CAST-128, which uses fixed S-boxes.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The adjacent diagram shows Blowfish's encryption routine.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] There are five subkey-arrays: one 18-entry P-array (denoted as K in the diagram, to avoid confusion with the Plaintext) and four 256-entry S-boxes (S0, S1, S2 and S3).
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The F-function splits the 32-bit input into four 8-bit quarters and uses the quarters as input to the S-boxes.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The S-boxes accept 8-bit input and produce 32-bit output.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The outputs are added modulo 232 and XORed to produce the final 32-bit output (see image in the upper right corner).
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] After the 16th round, undo the last swap, and XOR L with K18 and R with K17 (output whitening).
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Decryption is exactly the same as encryption, except that P1, P2, ..., P18 are used in the reverse order.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] This is not so obvious because xor is commutative and associative.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] A common misconception is to use inverse order of encryption as decryption algorithm (i.e. first XORing P17 and P18 to the ciphertext block, then using the P-entries in reverse order).
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish's key schedule starts by initializing the P-array and S-boxes with values derived from the hexadecimal digits of pi, which contain no obvious pattern (see nothing up my sleeve number).
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The secret key is then, byte by byte, cycling the key if necessary, XORed with all the P-entries in order.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] A 64-bit all-zero block is then encrypted with the algorithm as it stands.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The resultant ciphertext replaces P1 and P2.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The same ciphertext is then encrypted again with the new subkeys, and the new ciphertext replaces P3 and P4.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] This continues, replacing the entire P-array and all the S-box entries.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] In all, the Blowfish encryption algorithm will run 521 times to generate all the subkeys – about 4 KB of data is processed.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Because the P-array is 576 bits long, and the key bytes are XORed through all these 576 bits during the initialization, many implementations support key sizes up to 576 bits.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The reason for that is a discrepancy between the original Blowfish description, which uses 448-bit keys, and its reference implementation, which uses 576-bit keys.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The test vectors for verifying third-party implementations were also produced with 576-bit keys.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] When asked which Blowfish version is the correct one, Bruce Schneier answered: "The test vectors should be used to determine the one true Blowfish".
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Another opinion is that the 448 bits limit is present to ensure that every bit of every subkey depends on every bit of the key, as the last four values of the P-array don't affect every bit of the ciphertext.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] This point should be taken in consideration for implementations with a different number of rounds, as even though it increases security against an exhaustive attack, it weakens the security guaranteed by the algorithm.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] And given the slow initialization of the cipher with each change of key, it is granted a natural protection against brute-force attacks, which doesn't really justify key sizes longer than 448 bits.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish is a fast block cipher, except when changing keys.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Each new key requires the pre-processing equivalent of encrypting about 4 kilobytes of text, which is very slow compared to other block ciphers.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] This prevents its use in certain applications, but is not a problem in others.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish must be initialized with a key.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] It is good practice to have this key hashed with a hash function before use.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish has a memory footprint of just over 4 kilobytes of RAM.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] This constraint is not a problem even for older desktop and laptop computers, though it does prevent use in the smallest embedded systems such as early smartcards.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish was one of the first secure block ciphers not subject to any patents and therefore freely available for anyone to use.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] This benefit has contributed to its popularity in cryptographic software.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] bcrypt is a password hashing function which, combined with a variable number of iterations (work "cost"), exploits the expensive key setup phase of Blowfish to increase the workload and duration of hash calculations, further reducing threats from brute force attacks.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] bcrypt is also the name of a cross-platform file encryption utility developed in 2002 that implements Blowfish.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish's use of a 64-bit block size (as opposed to e.g.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] AES's 128-bit block size) makes it vulnerable to birthday attacks, particularly in contexts like HTTPS.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] In 2016, the SWEET32 attack demonstrated how to leverage birthday attacks to perform plaintext recovery (i.e. decrypting ciphertext) against ciphers with a 64-bit block size.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] The GnuPG project recommends that Blowfish not be used to encrypt files larger than 4 GB due to its small block size.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] A reduced-round variant of Blowfish is known to be susceptible to known-plaintext attacks on reflectively weak keys.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish implementations use 16 rounds of encryption, and are not susceptible to this attack.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Bruce Schneier has recommended migrating to his Blowfish successor, Twofish.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish2 was released in 2005, developed by Alexander Pukall.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] It has exactly the same design but has twice as many S tables and uses 64-bit integers instead of 32-bit integers.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] It no longer works on 64-bit blocks but on 128-bit blocks like AES.
[src:fabrik-inc/blowfish-cipher] Blowfish2 is used for example, in FreePascal.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 2010, Hitachi Data Systems sold through direct and indirect channels in more than 170 countries and regions, with customers that included over half of the Fortune 100 companies at the time.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] It was a subsidiary of Hitachi and part of the Hitachi Information Systems & Telecommunications Division until 2017.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 2017, it merged with Pentaho and Hitachi Insight Group to form Hitachi Vantara.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Itel was founded in 1967 by Peter Redfield and Gary Friedman as an equipment leasing company and initially focused on leasing IBM mainframes.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Through creative financial arrangements and investments, Itel began to lease IBM mainframes to customers at lower costs, which led to Itel ranking second to IBM in revenues.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 1977, a joint venture between National Semiconductor and Hitachi formed, and was contracted by Itel to manufacture IBM-compatible mainframes branded as Advanced Systems.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] After initial success shipping 200 such systems and net profits of $73 million, Itel increased investments and personnel to market its Advanced Systems brand.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] When Itel requested lower prices to compete with IBM, the CEO of National Semiconductor Charlie Sporck, persuaded Itel to commit to long-term contracts with National Semiconductor and Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] When news leaked that IBM was releasing a superior line of computers, customers held back purchases of Itel goods, causing Itel's inventory to build up drastically.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi agreed to Itel's request to cut back on shipment, but National Semiconductor insisted that National had blackmailed Itel.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 1979, Redfield was forced to resign as CEO.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] National Semiconductor took over Itel Advanced Systems' sales and marketing divisions.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] National Semiconductor renamed the National Advanced Systems (NAS) division, assembling and selling IBM-compatibles where the central processing unit (CPU) was imported from Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] National and Hitachi relied upon IBM's gradual and restrained roll-out of newer models to support IBM's technology and market share, which supported NAS's occasional successes.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] National Semiconductor and its subsidiary NAS were sued in 1983 by IBM for $2.5 billion on charges of using computer technology secrets stolen from IBM, as the result of an investigation by the United States Government into National's collaboration with Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi settled with IBM and licensed the mainframe operating system software from IBM.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 1983, NAS ceased manufacturing its line of mainframes (which had Hitachi processors) and became a reseller of Hitachi's mainframe and data storage products.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems (HDS) was founded in 1989 when Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) acquired National Advanced Systems (NAS) from National Semiconductor and renamed it Hitachi Data Systems.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Before that, the origins of the company had a history that stretched back to Itel, an early player in the mainframe market.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Intel's Computer Products Group sold National Semiconductors' IBM plug compatible mainframes.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 1979 National Semiconductor took over Itel and formed National Advanced Systems (NAS).
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] NAS shifted from manufacturing mainframes and began marketing systems from Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 1999, Hitachi bought out EDS's share, and HDS became a wholly owned subsidiary of Hitachi.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] For many years, HDS sold Hitachi IBM plug-compatible mainframes and storage systems, but in 2000, it exited the mainframe business and shifted its focus to enterprise storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] On February 28, 1989, National Semiconductor and Hitachi announced their agreement that Hitachi and Electronic Data Systems (EDS) would jointly acquire NAS for $398 million in cash, of which Hitachi would own 80%.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Memorex Telex and National had earlier, on January 10, 1989, announced plans on a joint venture "under which each company would own half of the unit and National would get $250 million plus four million shares of Memorex Telex".
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] By that time, Memorex Telex was able to arrange financing for the deal, but National had already accepted the Hitachi–EDS deal.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] The acquisition was envisaged to provide Hitachi with a better presence in the United States to compete with IBM.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] The entity was renamed Hitachi Data Systems (HDS).
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] On January 29, 1999, Hitachi announced it would take over EDS' stake in HDS, appointing Jun Naruse as CEO of its new subsidiary.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Naruse was an engineer with the RAID Systems Division who was involved in developing storage systems.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Having total control of the company, Hitachi infused Hitachi Data Systems with its corporate culture, ethics, and practices.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] On April 6, 2000, Hitachi Data Systems announced a re-organization to focus on storage systems rather than mainframes.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Shortly thereafter (June 26, 2000), the first HDS storage product was unveiled, the Freedom Storage Lightning 9900, featuring the crossbar switched architecture to interconnect memory, disks, servers, and other external devices instead of the traditional bus architecture.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In addition to HDS sales, HP OEM’d and Sun resold the 9900 and succeeding generations, which had additional capabilities such as virtualization of external Hitachi and third-party storage systems to form storage pools.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In January 2001, HDS announced the Thunder 9200, a mid-range modular storage system aimed at the small and medium business market, sold mainly through resellers.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems high-end and mid-range modular storage systems were complemented by software for storage management, content management, business continuity, replication, data protection, and IT operations.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 2002, Hitachi acquired Comstock Systems Corp, and analysts estimated that the acquisition would lead to a 35% percent market share.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] HDS moved to use the term cloud computing, culminating with an announcement on October 25, 2011.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In August 2014, in partnership with Avnet, HDS announced cloud partners.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] The corporate headquarters are in Santa Clara, California, with business offices in the United States, Australia and New Zealand, Canada, Latin America, Europe, the Middle East, and Africa.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] The culture of Hitachi Vantara is influenced by the values of Hitachi: wa (harmony, trust, and respect), Makoto (integrity, honesty), and kaitakusha-seishin (pioneering spirit and challenges).
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems appeared in *Fortune* magazine's "100 Best Companies to Work For" list in 2012, 2013 and 2014 and was ranked No.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] 8 in the *Fortune* list of top-paying companies in 2012.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Chief Executive Magazine gave HDS a ranking of No.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] 16 in its “40 Best Companies for Leaders” list for 2012.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems was recognized among the "Best Companies to Work For" in France and Poland in 2011.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] In 2010 Hitachi Data Systems was accredited by the Best Companies organization in the United Kingdom.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Synchronous TrueCopy causes each write to the primary volume to be performed to the secondary as well, and the I/O is considered complete only when updates to both primary and secondary have been completed.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Asynchronous TrueCopy stores time-stamped IO packets in the primary disk array and transfers them to the secondary array subject to link bandwidth.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] When the primary array's buffer is exhausted, it starts flagging tracks on the primary to be duplicated to the secondary when bandwidth permits.
[src:fabrik-inc/bluearc] Hitachi Data Systems has four types of partners: Technology, Global Systems Integrators, Hitachi TrueNorth Partners, and Hitachi TrueNorth Advisor Partners.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The company sells external hard drives and online backup software in a bundled product for consumers, small business users and audio/video (A/V) content creation professionals.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The company also hosts the free online digital content management and sharing site, Joggle.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Fabrik's product lines include SimpleTech, G-Technology, Joggle and Fabrik Ultimate Backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Fabrik was founded as a Smart network-attached storage (NAS) software company in August 2005 by former Maxtor executives Mike Cordano and Keyur Patel.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Patel hired a team of 4 led by founding VP of Engineering Robert Free, who designed and built the Maxtor Fusion NAS box that categorized media and supported visual sorting and searches.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Free developed new algorithms for optimized visual searches.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] This was acquired by Seagate and later used as the foundation for creating a web-based myfabrik.com.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Anaal Udaybabu designed a brand identity for on-the-web storage.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The following month, the company disclosed the completion of its series A funding of $4.1 million followed by $8 million in series B funding in July 2006 and $14.3 million in February 2007.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Then in May 2007, the company received $24.9 million in funding, bringing the total to about $51.3 million in funding.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] In February 2006, Fabrik partnered with Maxtor (acquired by Seagate in 2005) to develop Maxtor Fusion, a network-attached storage (NAS) device built for organizing and sharing digital files, and in late 2006 the company launched myfabrik.com, which organized and stored digital media online.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] In February 2007, the company acquired the consumer business of SimpleTech, inheriting the SimpleTech product line of external hard drives for consumers and small businesses.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] In January 2008, Fabrik acquired G-Technology and inherited a suite of external hard drives for Mac, creative pro, photography and A/V markets, including FireWire eSATA, USB, SCSI and Fibre Channel storage products.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Fabrik's acquisitions and the introduction of Joggle at the DEMO conference in January 2008 created four brands: SimpleTech, G-Technology, Joggle and Fabrik Ultimate Backup.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] SimpleTech and G-Technology products were still branded as such and maintained separate online website entities.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] On February 23, 2009, Hitachi Global Storage Technologies announced it agreed to acquire Fabrik.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] At this point Fabrik revenue for the year (2009) was estimated at $350M to $400M range and growing 40% on yearly basis.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] On April 6, 2009, Hitachi Global Storage Technologies completed the acquisition, which formed the core of Hitachi GST's new Branded Business division.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Following the acquisition, the subsidiary was branded 'G-Technology by Hitachi'.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The company's SimpleTech products are external hard drives for mainstream consumers and small business users.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] It includes portable external hard drives and desktop external hard drives.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] All SimpleTech products come bundled with free local backup software and online backup capabilities.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The SimpleTech [re]drive has a 100 percent recyclable enclosure and several energy and resource efficiency features.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The company claims the [re]drive is the world's most eco-friendly, resource conscious external hard drive.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The original design of the SimpleTech portable external storage product line was inspired by the Ferrari design team Pininfarina.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] Fabrik started a free online digital content management site called Joggle in early 2008.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The Web site searches for video, photos and music on a user's computer, external hard drive or online communities and networking sites and automatically consolidates it into a single online organizing and sharing tool.
[src:fabrik-inc/fabrik-inc] The company also has a pure online backup approach, Fabrik Ultimate Backup, where data can be backed up to remote servers using 128-bit SSL and Blowfish encryption.
